Red Wine Exploration by Elsayed Mustafa

This report explores a dataset containing wine quality and wines chemical attributes. In our exploration we will try determine what chemical attribute(s) affect wine quality.

We will be creating a new variable called quality.rating, which we will need to use in our multivariate analysis only, since multivariate plots can get messy otherwise.

pf$quality.rating <- ifelse(pf$quality < 6, 'low', ifelse(pf$quality < 7, 'average', 'high'))

We will also be removing x column since it doesnt help us.

pf$X = NULL

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1,599 red wines in the dataset with 12 features(fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality). Our output variable, quality ranges from 0 (worst) to 10 (best).

Other observations: * The residual.sugar median is 2.2. * The pH median 3.31. * The median for alcohol is 10.2, with most alcohol levels below 10. * Most red wines are rated with 5 and 6 quality.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features in the data set are alcohol and quality. Id like to determine which attributes best contribute to the quality of a red wine. I see that all our variables can be used in some combination to see what affects our red wine quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

From our plots, we can there are popular values in the making of the wine in all our variables, but well be checking the correlation of our variables with the quality to see which opinion we should follow.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes, Ive dropped the x column since its just counting rows, and created a new quality.rating variable to help us in our mulivaariate analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I thought volatile.acidity had an interesting bimodal distribution, its various spikes shows that it maybe depends on other chemical attributes as well, so does citric.acid with most of its values at 0, and some spikes at 0.25 and 0.5.

I did not perform any operations on the data, since it was cleaned beforehand.

Multivariate Plots Section

First feature well be looking at is citric.acid, since it has a strong relationship with five other variables and quality itself. From our univariate and bivariate analysis Weve indicated that quality increase with cetric.acid amounts of 0.25 up to 0.75 and thats the pattern well continue to see in our analysis, and well see what combination citric.acid has with other features that produce high quality wine.

Looks like, volatile.acidity clustered around 0.2 and 0.4 with a strong negative correlation for high quality.

In our bivariate analysis, we saw sulphates peaking at 0.9 when plotted against quality, but in combination with citric.acid, most points are clustered around 0.75 for high quality rating. overall there is a positive correlation between out two variables but not in high quality plot, seems sulphates around 0.75 is safest for quality.

fixed.acidity seem to have a strong positive correlation with citric.acid, which in turn impacts quality. Seems the best fit for high rating is to increase both amounts together up to a certain point, or at ~0 citric.acid we leave fixed.acidity at 5-8.

density seems to have a slight positive correlation with citric.acid, and the points arent clustered around any specific density amounts.

High quality rating seems to stem most from pH levels around 3.25. With a strong clear negative correlation between the two variables, it seems the higher citric.acid the lower we aim for pH levels to be.

When examining alcohol correlation with other variables, we saw a strong correlation of -50 with density, so we better have a look.

alcohol had the strongest impact on quality, which makes density an important factor to quality.

Weve noticed in our plot matrix a correlation between volatile.acidity and sulphates of -0.26, and a correlation between volatile.acidity and alcohol of -0.20. Lets check those out.

Around 0.75 sulphates and between 0.2 and 0.4 volatile.acidity seem the most dependable for high quality, but given the small correlation between these two variables at high rating, I will not depend on them the most to predict wine quality, a stronger relationship like sulphates and citric.acid would be more dependable.

Weve learned before that the higher the alcohol, the better the quality, and that volatile.acidity best ratings are around 0.2 up to 0.4, which is what is shown here for high quality.

Multivariate Analysis

  • citric.acid and pH certainly strengthened each other in relation to quality.
  • originally both variables had low correlation with quality but for high quality there was a specific combinaltions for those two variables to be at.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

  • The last two plots didnt show any patterns in terms of quality
  • It was surprising given that volatile.acidity, sulphates, and alcohol all had strong correlation with quality and a bit of correlation with each other.
  • In the end, all three variables seemed independent from one another.
  • citric.acid and pH was the most interesting, since all our acidic variables contribute to pH levels.
  • citric.acid had to be at specific amounts, to match the low or high pH levels gotten from volatile.acidity and fixed.acidity to get high quality.

Description Three

Reflection

We started our process by first getting some information about our dataset. Our dataset had 1599 observations and 13 variables, we dropped the variable X since it was useless and added the variable quality.rating so our plots will be more telling. Weve also seen general statistics about our variables (measures of center and measures of spread).

At the very start of our univariate analysis, weve seen that most wines had quality at 5-6 average rating, which was a big limitation to our analysis. A dataset with equal number of ratings would have strengthened the correlation with other variables(and maybe made us investigate them instead) since most points is not just at average ratings, and since the dataset is only 1599 rows we couldnt sample from it either to fit our need. Weve also seen the same thing in citric.acid and volatile.acidity histograms where they peaked at values (0 and 0.6 respectively) that later showed wasnt the optimum amounts for high quality.

Then we started our bivariate analysis with checking the correlation between quality and all other variable, and we choose the ones with strong correlation to further explore. Two relationships stood out for me, the first was between quality and alcohol percentage, where weve determined that up to 14% alcohol the quality mostly get better, there was one outlier near 15% alcohol that got a rating of 5, which doesnt benefit us much, since it was only one try. The second was between quality and citric.acid, most citric.acid was at zero, which according to our smooth line only gave an average of 5.5 quality, and there was a single outlier at one, which gave a rating of 4, most points of high rating (7 - 8) was between citric.acid of (2.5 - 7.5).

One of the things I noticed was how each one of these variables had a few instances of outliers that would make our smooth line decline. The problem with these few experiments, is that it doesnt really benefit us at all, because after trying it one or a few times, there is no guarantee that it was the main reason for getting low quality. That was another problem with our dataset. Other variables that we didnt investigate with quality might have been affected by outliers also and caused the low correlation they had. They might have had a strong correlation with quality up to a certain point.

From then, we started our multivariate analysis, where the quality.rating variable comes to use. There we started our analysis with citric.acid since it had many significant correlations with other variables. After implementing the plots weve seen how all the acidiv variables fit together, and which combinations have better chances to be high quality. Another plot we implemented was between alcohol and density by quality.rating, and weve discovered that density actually has a strong impact indirectly on quality, since it affects the strongest variable quality depends on.

Improvements that can be done for the dataset, include: * Increasing observations can give us more insight in our current outliers. * It will also help us sample from it to maybe get equal numbers of quality. * Adding a price variable should be interesting also.
